[2.833794, "o", "\r\n=== 4. CHEAPEST ANSWER ===\r\n$ hr route --prompt \"Say hello in Dutch\" --class free --pretty\r\n"]
[8.732541, "o", "✓ github_models/gpt-4o-mini  (~$0.000000, 1 tries)\r\n\r\nHello in Dutch is \"Hallo!\"\r\n"]
[9.262158, "o", "\r\n=== 5. AUTO-FALLBACK (free → paid if free fails) ===\r\n"]
[9.262301, "o", "$ hr route --prompt \"Why is the sky blue?\" --class free --auto-fallback --pretty\r\n"]
[23.142849, "o", "✓ github_models/gpt-4o-mini  (~$0.000000, 1 tries)\r\n\r\nThe sky appears blue primarily due to a phenomenon called Rayleigh scattering. When sunlight enters the Earth's atmosphere, it collides with gas molecules and particles. Sunlight is composed of various colors, each with different wavelengths. Blue light has a shorter wavelength compared to other colors like red or yellow.\r\n\r\nAs sunlight passes through the atmosphere, the shorter blue wavelengths are scattered in all directions by the small molecules in the air. Since blue light is scattered more than the other colors, we see a blue sky during the day. In contrast, during sunrise and sunset, the light has to pass through a larger volume of the atmosphere, scattering shorter wavelengths out of our line of sight and allowing the longer wavelengths (reds and oranges) to dominate, which is why we often see beautiful warm colors during those times.\r\n"]
